<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: NONFICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 65 YEARS OF THE OSCAR: The Official History of the Academy Awards by Robert 
Osborne (Abbeville Press: $59.95; 352 pp.). No sooner does a film reference 
book establish itself as essential than, more often than not, it either becomes 
outdated or goes out of print.So it is a special pleasure to welcome the 
up-to-the-minute third edition of this handsome volume by Hollywood Reporter 
columnist Osborne. Not only does it list every nominee and winner from 1927 
through last year (all included as well in a massive 27-page, 7,000 item 
index), it is unique among inclusive Oscar reference books by virtue of the 
number and quality of its hundreds of illustrations, including reproductions of 
the poster for each year's Best Picture winner. Turning these pages is easier 
than fighting the traffic to Monday night's awards ceremony, and even more 
rewarding. Kenneth Turan 
</P>
