<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'THE TRIALS OF OSCAR WILDE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When it was released in 1960, this timeless British film only had minor 
distribution and was up against the near-simultaneous "Oscar Wilde," with 
Robert Morley.Morley resembled Wilde more closely than Peter Finch (pictured, 
with Yvonne Mitchell), but Finch here is remarkable. Written and directed by 
Ken Hughes, this is a captivating period piece that introduces us to Wilde at 
the height of his fame and fortune. Yet Wilde, at 40, was already in the thrall 
of a disastrous infatuation with the pretty wastrel, Lord Alfred Douglas (Jon 
Fraser). What ensues is both a crackling good courtroom drama and a powerful 
work of social protest (TNT Thursday at 10:15 p.m.). Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</TEXT>
