<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S LOOTING OF A DIFFERENT TYPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * It has been several weeks since the Northridge earthquake, and my husband 
and I are still not sleeping. But it's not from the tremors that we all feel 
nor the destruction that we all see.It is from the selfishness, deceptiveness 
and ignorance which unfortunately have become our neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
 We moved to Northridge over four years ago but have never really gotten 
involved with our neighbors. The earthquake on Jan. 17 changed that forever. 
Overnight, Northridge was declared a disaster area, which meant federal 
disaster aid would be distributed and insurance deductibles had to be exceeded. 
</P>
<P>
 Suddenly our quiet neighborhood became a theater for con artists performing 
for insurance adjusters and Federal Emergency Management Agency inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
 Our relatives, friends and neighbors devised lists of lost personal items they 
never owned in order to exceed the high deductible on their insurance policies. 
Carpet, tiling and roofing destroyed before the earthquake were now held to be 
due to the earthquake. "How could they prove it didn't happen during the 
quake?" was everyone's reply when confronted. "You have to fudge a little or 
you won't get anything" was the advice of our neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
 The devastation of the earthquake has gone deeper than structural damage. It 
has brought about "financial looting" on every street in every neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
 LISA STEIN 
</P>
<P>
 Northridge 
</P>
</TEXT>
